notes on original: Notes on Color Plate 203: York Imperial apple, Kalmia Farm, Woodwardville, MD., collected August 4, 1909, M.B.W.  This represents a mild type of copper poisoning or Bordeaux injury occasionally noticed on York Imperial.  York Imperial is almost immune to ordinary bordeaux when the latter is prepared with excess of lime.  Slight enlargement of the lenticels and occasional small black or brownish specks together with a slight shrinking or failure to grow on the side getting the most spray and exposed to the sun represents the injury.  It is trivial and largely disappears on ripening.

notes on original: Kieffer pears injured by frost, 04/24/1905, after they were set. These Kieffer pears were full set, nearly 1/2 inch in diameter and were frozen through and through. Injured most on the inside, the ovules being all dead. The flesh of the pear was partly killed and ruptured.  The stamens and leaves were not hurt but all such fruits dropped off in a few days.

notes on original: Frost injury x6; New spur frozen Mar 29 at 25 degrees Fahrenheit when leaves were 3x1/2 inches.  This condition seems general.  Taken as of 10 am Mar 30.  After a second freeze of about same temperature but with less wind.  Evening of the 28 there was sleet followed by low temperature all night and considerable wind.  Ice at ground level 1/3 inch thick and ground well frozen.  Peticles, mid-ribs, etc. of leaves more or less blackened.  Several very backward limbs showing white but essential parts thoroughly blackened.

notes on original: Subject Apple Frost Injury.  Apple blossoms from Woodwardville, Maryland.  This shows the characteristic injury by frost which occurs when the apples are in bloom or in bud. The pistils and ovules being partly killed and the floral envelopes wholly uninjured.  The stamens are mostly uninjured, some of the inner ones having gone down with the ovary.  The youngest blossoms in bud at the time were not injured.  The most advanced flowers were hurt the most.

Waynesboro, Virginia, United States
notes on original: Frost injury on apple. Waynesboro, Virginia.  Specimens collected by Mr. J.W. Roberts, June 7, 1910. This frost occurred after the apples were well formed and apparently did not penetrate to the core. Instead of the usual procedure of the ovules dying first and the apple being injured more at the core than on the outside, the injury occurred mainly in the layer inside the outer tissue.  I suppose this represents the inner part of the tissue of corticle region.

notes on original: Chlorosis on probably Smock variety. Collected at Port Clinton, Ohio, Aug. 6, 1915 by M.B.W.  This peach tree was very much yellowed throughout, the leaves being almost a lemon yellow color, with green midrib and greenish veins and veinlets.  It resembles peach yellows to some extent, but was found too brightly colored.  The leaves were somewhat narrowed, but many of them full width.  The tree had all the symptoms of chlorosis without apparently symptoms of any other trouble.  The fruit was green, scarcely half grown, but approximately normal and scarce on this tree.  The region carries an abundance of lime and gypsum, there being large gypsum factories at both Port Clinton and Gypsum, near at hand.  The soil is a stiff clay, often with a stiff, pasty, bluish clay subsoil.  Undoubtedly a soil trouble.
